## Common PowerShell Commands <.ps1>

### Navigation & File Management
- `Get-ChildItem` ‚Äî List files and folders (alias: `ls`)
- `Set-Location <folder>` ‚Äî Change directory (alias: `cd`)
- `Clear-Host` ‚Äî Clear the screen (alias: `cls`)
- `Copy-Item <src> <dest>` ‚Äî Copy files
- `Move-Item <src> <dest>` ‚Äî Move/rename files
- `Remove-Item <file>` ‚Äî Delete files
- `New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path <folder>` ‚Äî Create directory
- `Get-Content <file>` ‚Äî View file contents
- `Rename-Item <old> <new>` ‚Äî Rename file

### Scripting & Automation

### System Info & Management

### Networking

### Disk & File Utilities

## Advanced CMD and PowerShell Options

---

### CMD Advanced
- `for /f "tokens=*" %i in (file.txt) do echo %i` ‚Äî Loop through lines in a file
- `set VAR=value` ‚Äî Set environment variable
- `call :label` ‚Äî Call a subroutine in a batch file
- `start <program>` ‚Äî Launch a program or script
- `schtasks /create ...` ‚Äî Schedule tasks
- `reg query <key>` ‚Äî Query Windows registry
- `wmic process list brief` ‚Äî Query system info with WMI
- `xcopy <src> <dest> /E /H /C /I` ‚Äî Advanced file copy
- `robocopy <src> <dest> /MIR` ‚Äî Robust file copy and sync

### PowerShell Advanced
- `Invoke-Command -ComputerName <host> -ScriptBlock { ... }` ‚Äî Run commands remotely
- `Enter-PSSession <host>` ‚Äî Start interactive remote session
- `New-ScheduledTaskTrigger` ‚Äî Create scheduled tasks
- `Register-ScheduledTask` ‚Äî Register scheduled tasks
- `Get-WmiObject -Class Win32_OperatingSystem` ‚Äî Query WMI objects
- `Export-Csv <file>` ‚Äî Export data to CSV
- `Import-Csv <file>` ‚Äî Import data from CSV
- `Send-MailMessage` ‚Äî Send email from PowerShell
- `Try { ... } Catch { ... }` ‚Äî Error handling in scripts
- `Write-Output`, `Write-Error`, `Write-Host` ‚Äî Output and logging
- `Measure-Command { ... }` ‚Äî Measure script execution time
- `Set-ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned` ‚Äî Allow running scripts

### Troubleshooting & Diagnostics
- `Get-WinEvent -LogName Application` ‚Äî View event logs
- `Get-Process | Where-Object { $_.CPU -gt 100 }` ‚Äî Find high CPU processes
- `Test-Path <path>` ‚Äî Check if a file or folder exists
- `Resolve-DnsName <host>` ‚Äî Advanced DNS lookup
- `Get-NetFirewallRule` ‚Äî List firewall rules
- `Get-Module` ‚Äî List loaded modules

---

## Tips for Using CMD and PowerShell
- Use `Tab` for auto-completion of commands and filenames.
- Use `help <command>` in CMD or `Get-Help <command>` in PowerShell for built-in help.
- Use `exit` to close the terminal.
- PowerShell supports aliases for many CMD commands (e.g., `ls`, `cd`, `cls`).
- PowerShell scripts use `.ps1` extension; CMD batch files use `.bat` or `.cmd`.

---

## Explanations
- **Remote Management**: PowerShell can manage remote systems using WinRM, SSH, or CIM sessions. Use `Invoke-Command` and `Enter-PSSession` for remote tasks.
- **Scripting & Automation**: Use loops (`ForEach-Object`, `for`), error handling (`Try/Catch`), and scheduled tasks for automation.
- **Data Export/Import**: Use `Export-Csv` and `Import-Csv` to work with tabular data.
- **Diagnostics**: Use event logs, process monitoring, and firewall rules to troubleshoot issues.
- **Security**: Use `Set-ExecutionPolicy` to control script permissions. Always review scripts before running from the internet.

For more advanced scenarios, see [PowerShell Gallery](https://www.powershellgallery.com/) and [Microsoft Docs](https://docs.microsoft.com/powershell/).

